I worked on a dataset with 100,000+ records to analyse how healthcare claims move through different stages — from initiation to approval or rejection.

The project highlights:
Inefficiencies in claim processing
Delays across different stages
Revenue leakage
High-risk hospitals affecting approval rates
The final output is an interactive Power BI dashboard designed to help stakeholders make data-driven decisions.


Tools & Technologies Used

SQL → Data extraction & transformation
Python (Pandas) → Data cleaning & preprocessing
Excel (Pivot Tables) → Data exploration & validation
Power BI → Dashboard & data visualisation

Data Cleaning & Preparation
Using SQL:
Extracted and structured raw data
Renamed columns and fixed inconsistencies

Using Python (Pandas):
Handled missing values
Fixed incorrect data types
Removed duplicates
Created derived columns:
Claim processing delays
Approval ratios
Revenue metrics

Data Exploration (Excel)
Used Pivot Tables to:
Validate cleaned data
Summarise key metrics
Identify trends quickly

Dashboard Features (Power BI)
The interactive dashboard includes:
KPI Cards
Total Cases
Approval %
Revenue Loss
Funnel Chart
Visualises the claim lifecycle
Delay Analysis
Identifies bottlenecks in each stage
Revenue Loss by Hospital
Highlights financial leakage
Risk Analysis (Scatter Plot)
Detects high-risk hospitals
Dynamic KPI Selector
Allows interactive insights


Key Insights 

Significant delays exist in the claim processing stages
Certain hospitals have higher risk scores and lower approval rates
There is clear revenue leakage between initiated and approved claims
The overall process is not fully optimised, leading to inefficiencies

Conclusion

This project shows how data analysis can uncover hidden inefficiencies in healthcare operations.

By improving claim processing workflows, reducing delays, and addressing high-risk areas, organisations can:
Increase approval rates
Reduce revenue loss
Improve operational efficiency
The dashboard provides a clear, data-driven foundation for better decision-making.


